  "questions": [
    {
      "text": "A 54-year-old woman comes to the physician because of a 3-month history of upper back pain. The pain is severe, dull in quality, and worse during the night. Physical examination shows a lump in the lower lateral quadrant of the right breast. Examination of the back shows tenderness over the thoracic spinous processes. Neurological examination shows no abnormalities. An x-ray of the thoracic spine shows vertebral osteolytic lesions at the levels of T4 and T5. A biopsy of the breast lump confirms the diagnosis of invasive ductal carcinoma. The patient's thoracic spine lesions are most likely a result of metastatic spread via which of the following structures?",
      "choices": [
        {
          "id": 1,
          "text": "Internal mammary lymph nodes"
        },
        {
          "id": 2,
          "text": "Azygos vein"
        },
        {
          "id": 3,
          "text": "Thyrocervical trunk"
        },
        {
          "id": 4,
          "text": "Thoracic duct"
        },
        {
          "id": 5,
          "text": "Intercostal artery"
        }
      ],
      "correct_choice_id": 2,
      "solution": "<div><h4 style='color: #f87171; font-weight: bold; margin-top: 16px; font-size: 1.125rem;'>A) INCORRECT:</h4>The <span data-sememe-id=\"MJdMuI0\">internal mammary lymph nodes</span> (<span data-sememe-id=\"MJdMuI0\">parasternal lymph nodes</span>) receive <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=960NMS&anker=Z1e7315a31bc800e90ec22cdf81497c3b\" data-learningcard-id=\"960NMS\" data-anker=\"Z1e7315a31bc800e90ec22cdf81497c3b\" data-section-id=\"0Ece8V0\" data-sememe-id=\"5oXic_\">lymph</a> from the <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=xo0EVS&anker=Z7461aaa50eeae708c4dba8bf8b41d291\" data-learningcard-id=\"xo0EVS\" data-anker=\"Z7461aaa50eeae708c4dba8bf8b41d291\" data-section-id=\"h_ccLU0\">medial</a> quadrants of the <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=B60zMS&anker=Z1b473b16a0c304b8376bbf09eefde16e\" data-learningcard-id=\"B60zMS\" data-anker=\"Z1b473b16a0c304b8376bbf09eefde16e\">breast</a> and only receive 10–25% of the <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=B60zMS&anker=Z1b473b16a0c304b8376bbf09eefde16e\" data-learningcard-id=\"B60zMS\" data-anker=\"Z1b473b16a0c304b8376bbf09eefde16e\">breast</a>'s <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=960NMS&anker=Z921256caa29f40142a9deeeecd5fbfb7\" data-learningcard-id=\"960NMS\" data-anker=\"Z921256caa29f40142a9deeeecd5fbfb7\" data-section-id=\"0Ece8V0\">lymphatic drainage</a>. <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=960NMS&anker=Z1e7315a31bc800e90ec22cdf81497c3b\" data-learningcard-id=\"960NMS\" data-anker=\"Z1e7315a31bc800e90ec22cdf81497c3b\" data-section-id=\"0Ece8V0\" data-sememe-id=\"5oXic_\">Lymph</a> from this patient's <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=B60zMS&anker=Z1b473b16a0c304b8376bbf09eefde16e\" data-learningcard-id=\"B60zMS\" data-anker=\"Z1b473b16a0c304b8376bbf09eefde16e\">breast</a> <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=WM0Png&anker=Z333a818dbf71a509f924e54006a41fb6\" data-learningcard-id=\"WM0Png\" data-anker=\"Z333a818dbf71a509f924e54006a41fb6\" data-section-id=\"azXQr00\">tumor</a>, which is located in the lower <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=xo0EVS&anker=Zad8f9786872edfa102f7204c82b56244\" data-learningcard-id=\"xo0EVS\" data-anker=\"Zad8f9786872edfa102f7204c82b56244\" data-section-id=\"h_ccLU0\">lateral</a> quadrant, would most likely drain into the <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=960NMS&anker=Z748f517ecdc29106e2738f88aa7530f4\" data-learningcard-id=\"960NMS\" data-anker=\"Z748f517ecdc29106e2738f88aa7530f4\" data-section-id=\"0Ece8V0\">axillary lymph nodes</a>. Moreover, lymphatic spread is not the most common route of <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=WM0Png&anker=Z56ce78424b29da57669d773285a33fa6\" data-learningcard-id=\"WM0Png\" data-anker=\"Z56ce78424b29da57669d773285a33fa6\" data-section-id=\"XzX9r00\" data-sememe-id=\"IrXYiz\">metastatic</a> spread from the <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=B60zMS&anker=Z1b473b16a0c304b8376bbf09eefde16e\" data-learningcard-id=\"B60zMS\" data-anker=\"Z1b473b16a0c304b8376bbf09eefde16e\">breast</a> to the <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=E6085S&anker=Z46dd80e8ba8f4ec5caa956e468a8c384\" data-learningcard-id=\"E6085S\" data-anker=\"Z46dd80e8ba8f4ec5caa956e468a8c384\">spine</a>.<img src='https://media-us.amboss.com/media/thumbs/big_6388a70823aed9.54879048.jpg' alt='Explanation Image' style='width: 100%; border-radius: 12px; margin-top: 16px;'><div style='margin-top: 16px; border-top: 1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.1); padding-top: 16px;'><h5 style='font-weight: bold; color: rgba(255,255,255,0.7); margin-bottom: 8px;'>Image Description:</h5><div style='font-size: 0.9em; color: rgba(255,255,255,0.9); line-height: 1.6;'><p>Lymphatics of the breast drain into three groups:</p><p>1. Axillary group, further divided into three levels<br/>– Level I: lateral to the lateral border of the pectoralis minor<br/>– Level II: behind the pectoralis minor<br/>– Level III: medial to the medial border of the pectoralis minor<br/>2. Parasternal (internal thoracic) group<br/>3. Posterior intercostal group (not shown here)<br/><br/>Efferent lymphatics travel to the supraclavicular nodes and terminate in the thoracic duct (on the left; not shown here) or the right lymphatic duct.</p></div></div></div><div><h4 style='color: #34d399; font-weight: bold; margin-top: 16px; font-size: 1.125rem;'>B) CORRECT:</h4>Blood from the <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=B60zMS&anker=Z1b473b16a0c304b8376bbf09eefde16e\" data-learningcard-id=\"B60zMS\" data-anker=\"Z1b473b16a0c304b8376bbf09eefde16e\">breast</a> drains into the <span data-sememe-id=\"3JXSF_\">ipsilateral</span> <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=0p0eLS&anker=Zbb552b3945e1e036794b1c8e4aab858a\" data-learningcard-id=\"0p0eLS\" data-anker=\"Zbb552b3945e1e036794b1c8e4aab858a\" data-section-id=\"PvcWZe0\" data-sememe-id=\"lscvEd0\">intercostal veins</a>. The <span class=\"wichtig\"><b><a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=Op0IpS&anker=Z022f54928d5fb969932d8f1abcbfaf1c\" data-learningcard-id=\"Op0IpS\" data-anker=\"Z022f54928d5fb969932d8f1abcbfaf1c\" data-section-id=\"YCcnqe0\" data-sememe-id=\"mIXVWz\">azygos vein</a></b></span> receives blood from the right <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=Op0IpS&anker=Z4ce2984d5971c73f3750bba9212816ed\" data-learningcard-id=\"Op0IpS\" data-anker=\"Z4ce2984d5971c73f3750bba9212816ed\" data-section-id=\"YCcnqe0\" data-sememe-id=\"O_XIo00\">posterior intercostal veins</a>. The <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=Op0IpS&anker=Z022f54928d5fb969932d8f1abcbfaf1c\" data-learningcard-id=\"Op0IpS\" data-anker=\"Z022f54928d5fb969932d8f1abcbfaf1c\" data-section-id=\"YCcnqe0\" data-sememe-id=\"mIXVWz\">azygos vein</a> has numerous <span class=\"wichtig\"><b><span data-sememe-id=\"1rY2Tq\">anastomoses</span> </b></span>with the <span class=\"wichtig\"><b><span data-sememe-id=\"OscIEd0\">vertebral venous plexus</span></b></span>, which is a longitudinal network of <span class=\"wichtig\"><b>valveless</b></span> <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=ZK0ZUS&anker=Z6f8d5f3537f44c7bd7f1915d726b6360\" data-learningcard-id=\"ZK0ZUS\" data-anker=\"Z6f8d5f3537f44c7bd7f1915d726b6360\" data-section-id=\"WJcPGW0\">veins</a> in the <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=E6085S&anker=Z46dd80e8ba8f4ec5caa956e468a8c384\" data-learningcard-id=\"E6085S\" data-anker=\"Z46dd80e8ba8f4ec5caa956e468a8c384\">spine</a> that includes the paravertebral <span data-sememe-id=\"FBcgcU0\">plexus of Batson</span>. The lack of valves in this network facilitates the spread of tumors and infections. Spinal <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=WM0Png&anker=Z56ce78424b29da57669d773285a33fa6\" data-learningcard-id=\"WM0Png\" data-anker=\"Z56ce78424b29da57669d773285a33fa6\" data-section-id=\"XzX9r00\" data-sememe-id=\"IrXYiz\">metastases</a> from <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=_k05qT&anker=Z3186a2e5e91124c9021effe4344433c7\" data-learningcard-id=\"_k05qT\" data-anker=\"Z3186a2e5e91124c9021effe4344433c7\" data-sememe-id=\"4M03Kg\">breast cancer</a> most commonly develop in the <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=E6085S&anker=Z94a49d3815bce219ca30fa0312d377a2\" data-learningcard-id=\"E6085S\" data-anker=\"Z94a49d3815bce219ca30fa0312d377a2\" data-section-id=\"rucfsV0\" data-sememe-id=\"Uj0b-f\">thoracic vertebrae</a>. A similar route via the <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=A60RnS&anker=Zc6c71165b125b93346e9e2fd41c92054\" data-learningcard-id=\"A60RnS\" data-anker=\"Zc6c71165b125b93346e9e2fd41c92054\" data-section-id=\"5EciwV0\" data-sememe-id=\"kTcmIb0\">internal iliac vein</a>, which connects the <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=l60vOS&anker=Z7a47e347acbec4a7e3466ff19dfff782\" data-learningcard-id=\"l60vOS\" data-anker=\"Z7a47e347acbec4a7e3466ff19dfff782\" data-section-id=\"jwc_ie0\" data-sememe-id=\"fsck8d0\">prostatic venous plexus</a> with the <span data-sememe-id=\"OscIEd0\">vertebral venous plexus</span>, is responsible for <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=WM0Png&anker=Z56ce78424b29da57669d773285a33fa6\" data-learningcard-id=\"WM0Png\" data-anker=\"Z56ce78424b29da57669d773285a33fa6\" data-section-id=\"XzX9r00\" data-sememe-id=\"IrXYiz\">metastasis</a> from <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=Ji0ssf&anker=Zfa2f5b29247f04c87601032b5ed92eec\" data-learningcard-id=\"Ji0ssf\" data-anker=\"Zfa2f5b29247f04c87601032b5ed92eec\" data-sememe-id=\"Al0RzT\">prostate cancer</a> to the <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=E6085S&anker=Zb4bb0653b6bc8be976796db51c6d79ca\" data-learningcard-id=\"E6085S\" data-anker=\"Zb4bb0653b6bc8be976796db51c6d79ca\" data-section-id=\"rucfsV0\">lumbar vertebrae</a>. Most <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=WM0Png&anker=Z22674f156f136302ff6142f806db0d5a\" data-learningcard-id=\"WM0Png\" data-anker=\"Z22674f156f136302ff6142f806db0d5a\" data-section-id=\"azXQr00\" data-sememe-id=\"58XiM-\">carcinomas</a> tend to <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=WM0Png&anker=Z56ce78424b29da57669d773285a33fa6\" data-learningcard-id=\"WM0Png\" data-anker=\"Z56ce78424b29da57669d773285a33fa6\" data-section-id=\"XzX9r00\" data-sememe-id=\"IrXYiz\">metastasize</a> lymphatically but <span class=\"wichtig\"><b><a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=oD002R&anker=Z3134d031d665d445006833ed1577753b\" data-learningcard-id=\"oD002R\" data-anker=\"Z3134d031d665d445006833ed1577753b\" data-sememe-id=\"d7aokN\">bone metastases</a></b></span> (especially spinal <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=WM0Png&anker=Z56ce78424b29da57669d773285a33fa6\" data-learningcard-id=\"WM0Png\" data-anker=\"Z56ce78424b29da57669d773285a33fa6\" data-section-id=\"XzX9r00\" data-sememe-id=\"IrXYiz\">metastases</a>) are most commonly the result of <span class=\"wichtig\"><b>hematogenous spread </b></span>rather than lymphatic spread.<img src='https://media-us.amboss.com/media/thumbs/big_5ad610708b3fd.jpg' alt='Explanation Image' style='width: 100%; border-radius: 12px; margin-top: 16px;'><div style='margin-top: 16px; border-top: 1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.1); padding-top: 16px;'><h5 style='font-weight: bold; color: rgba(255,255,255,0.7); margin-bottom: 8px;'>Image Description:</h5><div style='font-size: 0.9em; color: rgba(255,255,255,0.9); line-height: 1.6;'><p>Chest, neck, and abdomen (coronal section, ventral view)</p><p>The veins depicted here ultimately drain into the superior and the inferior vena cava.</p></div></div></div><div><h4 style='color: #f87171; font-weight: bold; margin-top: 16px; font-size: 1.125rem;'>C) INCORRECT:</h4>The <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=b60HjS&anker=Zb9a5f6bc1c815d4042f7cb63ef05a21a\" data-learningcard-id=\"b60HjS\" data-anker=\"Zb9a5f6bc1c815d4042f7cb63ef05a21a\" data-section-id=\"ZxcZEe0\" data-sememe-id=\"EpX8r_\">thyrocervical trunk</a> arises from the <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=b60HjS&anker=Z455368df00db1f7843027026db56ed9c\" data-learningcard-id=\"b60HjS\" data-anker=\"Z455368df00db1f7843027026db56ed9c\" data-section-id=\"ZxcZEe0\" data-sememe-id=\"vpXAr_\">subclavian artery</a> and gives rise to the <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=i60JkS&anker=Z5cea93ca86b858848829edf71f1ae7c5\" data-learningcard-id=\"i60JkS\" data-anker=\"Z5cea93ca86b858848829edf71f1ae7c5\" data-section-id=\"uFcpPV0\" data-sememe-id=\"-hcDgX0\">inferior thyroid artery</a>, <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=cK0a2S&anker=Z5f2c14a303ab9aeeb1815e52e4507468\" data-learningcard-id=\"cK0a2S\" data-anker=\"Z5f2c14a303ab9aeeb1815e52e4507468\" data-section-id=\"_Jc59W0\" data-sememe-id=\"Tj16-g0\">suprascapular artery</a>, <span data-sememe-id=\"nJd7uI0\">transverse cervical artery</span>, and <span data-sememe-id=\"oJd0EI0\">ascending cervical artery</span>. The <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=b60HjS&anker=Zb9a5f6bc1c815d4042f7cb63ef05a21a\" data-learningcard-id=\"b60HjS\" data-anker=\"Zb9a5f6bc1c815d4042f7cb63ef05a21a\" data-section-id=\"ZxcZEe0\" data-sememe-id=\"EpX8r_\">thyrocervical trunk</a> is a potential route for <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=WM0Png&anker=Z56ce78424b29da57669d773285a33fa6\" data-learningcard-id=\"WM0Png\" data-anker=\"Z56ce78424b29da57669d773285a33fa6\" data-section-id=\"XzX9r00\" data-sememe-id=\"IrXYiz\">metastasis</a> of <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=nh07ef&anker=Z3ff7ac92fae21c5ca2363549c47bb7e7\" data-learningcard-id=\"nh07ef\" data-anker=\"Z3ff7ac92fae21c5ca2363549c47bb7e7\" data-sememe-id=\"sk0t6T\">lung cancer</a> to the <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=cK0a2S&anker=Z5465b1c25700d076f1d19237743739be\" data-learningcard-id=\"cK0a2S\" data-anker=\"Z5465b1c25700d076f1d19237743739be\" data-section-id=\"5xciCe0\">scapula</a> (via the <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=cK0a2S&anker=Z5f2c14a303ab9aeeb1815e52e4507468\" data-learningcard-id=\"cK0a2S\" data-anker=\"Z5f2c14a303ab9aeeb1815e52e4507468\" data-section-id=\"_Jc59W0\" data-sememe-id=\"Tj16-g0\">suprascapular artery</a>) and <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=E6085S&anker=Zc37bea07a25afadd1213b05b7b86fc03\" data-learningcard-id=\"E6085S\" data-anker=\"Zc37bea07a25afadd1213b05b7b86fc03\" data-section-id=\"rucfsV0\" data-sememe-id=\"2j0T-f\">cervical vertebrae</a> (via the <span data-sememe-id=\"oJd0EI0\">ascending cervical artery</span>) but is not a potential route for <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=WM0Png&anker=Z56ce78424b29da57669d773285a33fa6\" data-learningcard-id=\"WM0Png\" data-anker=\"Z56ce78424b29da57669d773285a33fa6\" data-section-id=\"XzX9r00\" data-sememe-id=\"IrXYiz\">metastasis</a> of <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=_k05qT&anker=Z3186a2e5e91124c9021effe4344433c7\" data-learningcard-id=\"_k05qT\" data-anker=\"Z3186a2e5e91124c9021effe4344433c7\" data-sememe-id=\"4M03Kg\">breast cancer</a> to the <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=E6085S&anker=Z94a49d3815bce219ca30fa0312d377a2\" data-learningcard-id=\"E6085S\" data-anker=\"Z94a49d3815bce219ca30fa0312d377a2\" data-section-id=\"rucfsV0\" data-sememe-id=\"Uj0b-f\">thoracic spine</a>.<img src='https://media-us.amboss.com/media/thumbs/big_5975f842bc36c.jpg' alt='Explanation Image' style='width: 100%; border-radius: 12px; margin-top: 16px;'><div style='margin-top: 16px; border-top: 1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.1); padding-top: 16px;'><h5 style='font-weight: bold; color: rgba(255,255,255,0.7); margin-bottom: 8px;'>Image Description:</h5><div style='font-size: 0.9em; color: rgba(255,255,255,0.9); line-height: 1.6;'><p>Ventral view</p><p>The left subclavian artery arises directly from the arch of aorta. The right subclavian artery arises from the brachiocephalic artery. At the outer border of the first rib, the subclavian arteries continue as the axillary arteries. The main branches of the subclavian artery (from proximal to distal) are:<br/>- Internal thoracic artery (internal mammary artery)<br/>- Vertebral artery<br/>- Thyrocervical trunk<br/>- Costocervical trunk</p></div></div></div><div><h4 style='color: #f87171; font-weight: bold; margin-top: 16px; font-size: 1.125rem;'>D) INCORRECT:</h4>The <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=960NMS&anker=Z77e3eae478e825109a2d75de7caa8c55\" data-learningcard-id=\"960NMS\" data-anker=\"Z77e3eae478e825109a2d75de7caa8c55\" data-section-id=\"0Ece8V0\" data-sememe-id=\"NoY-XJ\">thoracic duct</a> (<a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=960NMS&anker=Z77e3eae478e825109a2d75de7caa8c55\" data-learningcard-id=\"960NMS\" data-anker=\"Z77e3eae478e825109a2d75de7caa8c55\" data-section-id=\"0Ece8V0\" data-sememe-id=\"NoY-XJ\">left lymphatic duct</a>), which receives <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=960NMS&anker=Z921256caa29f40142a9deeeecd5fbfb7\" data-learningcard-id=\"960NMS\" data-anker=\"Z921256caa29f40142a9deeeecd5fbfb7\" data-section-id=\"0Ece8V0\">lymphatic drainage</a> from the left <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=960NMS&anker=Z748f517ecdc29106e2738f88aa7530f4\" data-learningcard-id=\"960NMS\" data-anker=\"Z748f517ecdc29106e2738f88aa7530f4\" data-section-id=\"0Ece8V0\">axillary lymph nodes</a> and drains into the left <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=b60HjS&anker=Zc5eaaf0585539be9f602ca12aeaa21ef\" data-learningcard-id=\"b60HjS\" data-anker=\"Zc5eaaf0585539be9f602ca12aeaa21ef\" data-section-id=\"ZxcZEe0\" data-sememe-id=\"41c3SY0\">subclavian vein</a>, is a potential route for <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=nh07ef&anker=Z10e1e58497265a96d804a98d36fd497b\" data-learningcard-id=\"nh07ef\" data-anker=\"Z10e1e58497265a96d804a98d36fd497b\" data-section-id=\"82aOjP\">pulmonary metastasis</a> in the case of left-sided <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=_k05qT&anker=Z3186a2e5e91124c9021effe4344433c7\" data-learningcard-id=\"_k05qT\" data-anker=\"Z3186a2e5e91124c9021effe4344433c7\" data-sememe-id=\"4M03Kg\">breast carcinoma</a> but it is not a likely route for <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=WM0Png&anker=Z56ce78424b29da57669d773285a33fa6\" data-learningcard-id=\"WM0Png\" data-anker=\"Z56ce78424b29da57669d773285a33fa6\" data-section-id=\"XzX9r00\" data-sememe-id=\"IrXYiz\">metastasis</a> of right-sided <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=_k05qT&anker=Z3186a2e5e91124c9021effe4344433c7\" data-learningcard-id=\"_k05qT\" data-anker=\"Z3186a2e5e91124c9021effe4344433c7\" data-sememe-id=\"4M03Kg\">breast cancer</a>. Moreover, lymphatic spread is not the most common route of <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=WM0Png&anker=Z56ce78424b29da57669d773285a33fa6\" data-learningcard-id=\"WM0Png\" data-anker=\"Z56ce78424b29da57669d773285a33fa6\" data-section-id=\"XzX9r00\" data-sememe-id=\"IrXYiz\">metastatic</a> spread from the <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=B60zMS&anker=Z1b473b16a0c304b8376bbf09eefde16e\" data-learningcard-id=\"B60zMS\" data-anker=\"Z1b473b16a0c304b8376bbf09eefde16e\">breast</a> to the <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=E6085S&anker=Z46dd80e8ba8f4ec5caa956e468a8c384\" data-learningcard-id=\"E6085S\" data-anker=\"Z46dd80e8ba8f4ec5caa956e468a8c384\">spine</a>.<img src='https://media-us.amboss.com/media/thumbs/big_60e31bc0a6dc8.jpg' alt='Explanation Image' style='width: 100%; border-radius: 12px; margin-top: 16px;'><div style='margin-top: 16px; border-top: 1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.1); padding-top: 16px;'><h5 style='font-weight: bold; color: rgba(255,255,255,0.7); margin-bottom: 8px;'>Image Description:</h5><div style='font-size: 0.9em; color: rgba(255,255,255,0.9); line-height: 1.6;'><p>Lymph is drained into the systemic circulation via the subclavian veins. The right lymphatic duct primarily drains the upper right side of the body (green overlay). The thoracic duct is responsible for draining the rest of the body.</p><p>Testicular tumors do not typically disseminate to scrotal lymph nodes, because the two organs have separate lymphatic systems: testes drain to the para-aortic nodes and the scrotum drains to superficial inguinal nodes.</p></div></div></div><div><h4 style='color: #f87171; font-weight: bold; margin-top: 16px; font-size: 1.125rem;'>E) INCORRECT:</h4>The <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=xo0EVS&anker=Z611d380c96ce797875c8e46c949415ed\" data-learningcard-id=\"xo0EVS\" data-anker=\"Z611d380c96ce797875c8e46c949415ed\" data-section-id=\"h_ccLU0\">anterior</a> <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=0p0eLS&anker=Z900b0459efed171b6183dbbbb2da52b9\" data-learningcard-id=\"0p0eLS\" data-anker=\"Z900b0459efed171b6183dbbbb2da52b9\" data-section-id=\"PvcWZe0\" data-sememe-id=\"PscWEd0\">intercostal arteries</a> (branches of the <span data-sememe-id=\"3JXSF_\">ipsilateral</span> <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=b60HjS&anker=Z32dfe26f12419fb621b24dbe75284358\" data-learningcard-id=\"b60HjS\" data-anker=\"Z32dfe26f12419fb621b24dbe75284358\" data-section-id=\"ZxcZEe0\" data-sememe-id=\"TZc6aa0\">internal thoracic artery</a>) and <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=Op0IpS&anker=Z8a61017ca6daf11a486a747c23c44e54\" data-learningcard-id=\"Op0IpS\" data-anker=\"Z8a61017ca6daf11a486a747c23c44e54\" data-section-id=\"YCcnqe0\">posterior intercostal arteries</a> (<a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=Op0IpS&anker=Z7e355560468ff22d3a69a1b87f58f7d8\" data-learningcard-id=\"Op0IpS\" data-anker=\"Z7e355560468ff22d3a69a1b87f58f7d8\" data-section-id=\"YCcnqe0\">branches of the thoracic aorta</a>) are potential routes for <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=WM0Png&anker=Z56ce78424b29da57669d773285a33fa6\" data-learningcard-id=\"WM0Png\" data-anker=\"Z56ce78424b29da57669d773285a33fa6\" data-section-id=\"XzX9r00\" data-sememe-id=\"IrXYiz\">metastasis</a> of <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=nh07ef&anker=Z3ff7ac92fae21c5ca2363549c47bb7e7\" data-learningcard-id=\"nh07ef\" data-anker=\"Z3ff7ac92fae21c5ca2363549c47bb7e7\" data-sememe-id=\"sk0t6T\">lung cancer</a> to structures of the thoracic wall (e.g., <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=0p0eLS&anker=Z3bb4f01e3bc36c0d0d72735e6ddbb716\" data-learningcard-id=\"0p0eLS\" data-anker=\"Z3bb4f01e3bc36c0d0d72735e6ddbb716\" data-section-id=\"OxcI9e0\">ribs</a>); they are not routes for <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=WM0Png&anker=Z56ce78424b29da57669d773285a33fa6\" data-learningcard-id=\"WM0Png\" data-anker=\"Z56ce78424b29da57669d773285a33fa6\" data-section-id=\"XzX9r00\" data-sememe-id=\"IrXYiz\">metastasis</a> of <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=_k05qT&anker=Z3186a2e5e91124c9021effe4344433c7\" data-learningcard-id=\"_k05qT\" data-anker=\"Z3186a2e5e91124c9021effe4344433c7\" data-sememe-id=\"4M03Kg\">breast cancer</a> to the <a href=\"https://www.amboss.com/us/library#xid=E6085S&anker=Z94a49d3815bce219ca30fa0312d377a2\" data-learningcard-id=\"E6085S\" data-anker=\"Z94a49d3815bce219ca30fa0312d377a2\" data-section-id=\"rucfsV0\" data-sememe-id=\"Uj0b-f\">thoracic spine</a>.<img src='https://media-us.amboss.com/media/thumbs/big_5b6999580e120.jpg' alt='Explanation Image' style='width: 100%; border-radius: 12px; margin-top: 16px;'><div style='margin-top: 16px; border-top: 1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.1); padding-top: 16px;'><h5 style='font-weight: bold; color: rgba(255,255,255,0.7); margin-bottom: 8px;'>Image Description:</h5><div style='font-size: 0.9em; color: rgba(255,255,255,0.9); line-height: 1.6;'><p>Illustration of the intercostal artery, vein, and nerve (forming the intercostal neurovascular bundle) within the costal groove</p><p>As the pathway of these structures follows the inferior edge of the ribs, medical interventions (e.g., chest tube insertion) are always performed along the superior edge of the rib. The order of the structures of the neurovascular bundle can be remembered using the acronym “VAN”: the intercostal vein (V) is superior, the artery (A) is in the middle, and the nerve (N) is inferior.</p></div></div></div>",
